n powers to the rest of the world, mainly for the purpose of furthering colonial forms of domination in the economic, political, military, legal and cultural spheres. By contrast, this edited volume highlights the relevance of both European and non-European understandings of piracy to the development of global maritime security and freedom of navigation. It explores the significance of 'legal posturing' on the part of those accused of piracy, as well as the existence of non-European laws and regulations regarding piracy and related forms of maritime violence in the early modern era. The authors in this volume highlight cases from various parts of the early-modern world, thereby explaining piracy as a global phenomenon.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0https://www.aup.nl/en/publish/open-access  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 4aEarly Modern Studies. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 4aInternational Relations. 4aPolitics and Government. 7aHISTORY / Modern / General.2bisacsh  aPiracy, maritime history, violence, crime, global history.1 aAmirell, Stefan Eklöf, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAmirell, Stefan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aAntony, Robert J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBenton, Lauren, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuchan, Bruce, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuchan, Bruce, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGaynor, Jennifer L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHägerdal, Hans, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHägerdal, Hans